iI've had people go spelunking down into my own blog [2] archives		gopher.black	70
ibefore and I have to say it's a really cool feeling. Journaling is		gopher.black	70
iinherently about yourself. When another human decides to spend		gopher.black	70
itheir time reading your personal thoughts and history, it's very		gopher.black	70
iflattering (at least to me).		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
h[2] tomasino blog	URL:https://blog.tomasino.org
i		gopher.black	70
iThere are technical blogs aplenty which focus on code or math or		gopher.black	70
iscience or whatever topic that isn't the self. They're great too,		gopher.black	70
ibut I don't see them the same way. I'm sure they provide great		gopher.black	70
iinterest to people when they're published, and interesting history		gopher.black	70
ito those that come later. Sharing a personal blog is so much more		gopher.black	70
iintimate. Keeping one up for an extended period of time is its own		gopher.black	70
itype of vulnerability. It's not just showing your timely thoughts		gopher.black	70
iof today, but also the cringe-worthy worries of younger you. It's		gopher.black	70
ieasy to spotlight the mistakes, the lack of understanding, and the		gopher.black	70
iideas that you'd eventually grow out of. That's beautiful stuff,		gopher.black	70
iif horribly embarrassing.		gopher.black	70
